Based on below details create a readme file for github:

project description :

Fake News Classification

About Dataset
(WELFake) is a dataset of 72,134 news articles with 35,028 real and 37,106 fake news. For this, authors merged four popular news datasets (i.e. Kaggle, McIntire, Reuters, BuzzFeed Political) to prevent over-fitting of classifiers and to provide more text data for better ML training.

Dataset contains four columns: Serial number (starting from 0); Title (about the text news heading); Text (about the news content); and Label (0 = fake and 1 = real).

There are 78098 data entries in csv file out of which only 72134 entries are accessed as per the data frame.

Published in:
IEEE Transactions on Computational Social Systems: pp. 1-13 (doi: 10.1109/TCSS.2021.3068519).

steps performed:
1. EDA
2. Data processing 
3. Modeing 
 - Naive Bayes Classifier
Logistic Regression
- Support Vector Machine
- Random Forest Classifier
- Neural network using Tokenization and Padding
_ Long Short Term Memory Neural Network
4. results :
Accuracy - Naive Bayes : 0.84
Accuracy - Logistic regression: 0.94
Accuracy - Support Vector Machine: 0.94
Accuracy - Random Forest Algorithm: 0.95
Accuracy - Neural network : 0.93
Accuracy - LSMT Neural network: 0.94
5. Summary
We have effectively used exploratory data analysis, data preprocessing, and modeling techniques in our optional project "Fake news classification" to categorize fake news. We put into practice a wide range of machine learning algorithms, from more complex neural network architectures, such as an LSTM-based network, to more conventional methods like Naive Bayes, Logistic Regression, SVM, and Random Forest.
The Random Forest Classifier showed highest accuracy among the traditional ML models, achieving 95%. However, both the LSTM neural network and SVM showcased competitive performance with accuracies of 94%. These results indicate the effectiveness of different modeling techniques in distinguishing between real and fake news articles, with neural networks and ensemble methods demonstrating promising results.
Overall, our project provides a thorough exploration of multiple approaches for fake news classification, offering insights into various models' strengths and performances.</div></div></div><div md:gap-3"><div class="flex flex-grow flex-col max-w-full"><div data-message-author-role="assistant" data-message-id="93fc69d9-e995-4217-928c-2c9ce62f89a9" class="min-h-[20px] text-message flex flex-col items-start gap-3 whitespace-pre-wrap break-words [.text-message+&amp;]:mt-5 overflow-x-auto"><div class="markdown prose w-full break-words dark:prose-invert dark"><h1>Fake News Classification Project</h1><h2>Overview</h2><p>This repository contains the code and resources for a Fake News Classification project. The primary goal of this project is to develop and evaluate various machine learning models for distinguishing between real and fake news articles.</p><h2>Dataset</h2><p>The dataset used for this project, named WELFake, consists of 72,134 news articles. It includes 35,028 real news articles and 37,106 fake news articles. The dataset is a combination of four popular news datasets (Kaggle, McIntire, Reuters, BuzzFeed Political) to prevent overfitting and enhance the model's training data. Each entry in the dataset has four columns: Serial number, Title, Text, and Label (0 for fake, 1 for real).</p><p>The dataset has been published in IEEE Transactions on Computational Social Systems, with the reference: DOI 10.1109/TCSS.2021.3068519.</p><h2>Steps Performed</h2><ol><li><p><strong>Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA):</strong> Analyzed the dataset to gain insights into its structure and characteristics.</p></li><li><p><strong>Data Processing:</strong> Preprocessed the data to prepare it for model training, including cleaning and handling missing values.</p></li><li><p><strong>Modeling:</strong> Implemented various machine learning algorithms for classification:</p><ul><li>Naive Bayes Classifier</li><li>Logistic Regression</li><li>Support Vector Machine</li><li>Random Forest Classifier</li><li>Neural Network using Tokenization and Padding</li><li>Long Short Term Memory (LSTM) Neural Network</li></ul></li><li><p><strong>Results:</strong></p><ul><li>Accuracy - Naive Bayes: 0.84</li><li>Accuracy - Logistic Regression: 0.94</li><li>Accuracy - Support Vector Machine: 0.94</li><li>Accuracy - Random Forest Algorithm: 0.95</li><li>Accuracy - Neural Network: 0.93</li><li>Accuracy - LSTM Neural Network: 0.94</li></ul></li><li><p><strong>Summary:</strong></p><p>This project showcases the application of exploratory data analysis, data preprocessing, and various machine learning algorithms for fake news classification. Multiple models, ranging from traditional machine learning algorithms to complex neural network architectures, were explored. The Random Forest Classifier achieved the highest accuracy at 95%, while both LSTM Neural Network and SVM demonstrated competitive performance with accuracies of 94%.</p><p>These results highlight the effectiveness of different modeling techniques in distinguishing between real and fake news articles. The project provides valuable insights into the strengths and performances of various models, offering a comprehensive exploration of approaches for fake news classification.</p></li></ol><h2>How to Use</h2><ol><li><p>Clone the repository:</p><pre><div class="dark bg-gray-950 rounded-md"><div class="flex items-center relative text-token-text-secondary bg-token-main-surface-secondary px-4 py-2 text-xs font-sans justify-between rounded-t-md"><span>bash</span><span class="" data-state="closed"><button class="flex gap-1 items-center"><svg width="24" height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="icon-sm"><path fill-rule="evenodd" clip-rule="evenodd" d="M12 4C10.8954 4 10 4.89543 10 6H14C14 4.89543 13.1046 4 12 4ZM8.53513 4C9.22675 2.8044 10.5194 2 12 2C13.4806 2 14.7733 2.8044 15.4649 4H17C18.6569 4 20 5.34315 20 7V19C20 20.6569 18.6569 22 17 22H7C5.34315 22 4 20.6569 4 19V7C4 5.34315 5.34315 4 7 4H8.53513ZM8 6H7C6.44772 6 6 6.44772 6 7V19C6 19.5523 6.44772 20 7 20H17C17.5523 20 18 19.5523 18 19V7C18 6.44772 17.5523 6 17 6H16C16 7.10457 15.1046 8 14 8H10C8.89543 8 8 7.10457 8 6Z" fill="currentColor"></path></svg>Copy code</button></span></div><div class="p-4 overflow-y-auto"><code class="!whitespace-pre hljs language-bash">git <span class="hljs-built_in">clone</span> https://github.com/your-username/fake-news-classification.git

class="markdown prose w-full break-words dark:prose-invert dark"><p>Certainly! When creating a GitHub repository for your Fake News Classification project, you'll want to include the following items in your repository:</p><ol><li><p><strong>README.md:</strong></p><ul><li>Write a detailed README file providing an overview of the project, dataset details, steps performed, results, and how to use the code.</li></ul></li><li><p><strong>Code:</strong></p><ul><li>Include the Jupyter notebooks or Python scripts used for exploratory data analysis, data processing, and modeling.</li></ul></li><li><p><strong>Notebooks Directory:</strong></p><ul><li>If you used Jupyter notebooks, organize them into a dedicated directory (e.g., <code>notebooks</code>).</li></ul></li><li><p><strong>Dataset:</strong></p><ul><li>Include the dataset used for the project. If the dataset is too large, provide instructions on how to obtain it or provide a download link.</li></ul></li><li><p><strong>Requirements.txt:</strong></p><ul><li>List the dependencies for your project in a <code>requirements.txt</code> file so others can easily install them.</li></ul></li><li><p><strong>License:</strong></p><ul><li>Choose an appropriate open-source license for your project and include a <code>LICENSE</code> file.</li></ul></li><li><p><strong>.gitignore:</strong></p><ul><li>Create a <code>.gitignore</code> file to exclude unnecessary files or directories from version control.</li></ul></li><li><p><strong>Results Directory:</strong></p><ul><li>If you have any saved models or result files, consider organizing them into a <code>results</code> directory.</li></ul></li><li><p><strong>Contributing Guidelines:</strong></p><ul><li>If you want to encourage collaboration, include a <code>CONTRIBUTING.md</code> file with guidelines for contributors.</li></ul></li><li><p><strong>Documentation Directory:</strong></p><ul><li>If you have additional documentation, such as project notes or methodology, organize them into a <code>docs</code> directory.</li></ul></li><li><p><strong>Images Directory:</strong></p><ul><li>If you created visualizations or graphs, store them in an <code>images</code> directory.</li></ul></li><li><p><strong>Data Directory:</strong></p><ul><li>If your dataset is small, consider placing it in a <code>data</code> directory. If it's large, provide instructions on how to obtain it.</li></ul></li><li><p><strong>References:</strong></p><ul><li>Include a section in your README with references to any external sources or papers you used.</li></ul></li><li><p><strong>CI/CD Configuration:</strong></p><ul><li>If applicable, set up continuous integration (CI) and continuous deployment (CD) configurations, such as a <code>.travis.yml</code> file.</li></ul></li><li><p><strong>Acknowledgments:</strong></p><ul><li>If you used external code, libraries, or datasets, give credit in an acknowledgments section.</li></ul></li><li><p><strong>Usage Section:</strong></p><ul><li>Provide clear instructions on how others can use your code and reproduce your results.</li></ul></li></ol><p>Here's a simplified directory structure:</p><pre><div class="dark bg-gray-950 rounded-md"><div class="flex items-center relative text-token-text-secondary bg-token-main-surface-secondary px-4 py-2 text-xs font-sans justify-between rounded-t-md"><span>plaintext</span><span class="" data-state="closed"><button class="flex gap-1 items-center"><svg width="24" height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="icon-sm"><path fill-rule="evenodd" clip-rule="evenodd" d="M12 4C10.8954 4 10 4.89543 10 6H14C14 4.89543 13.1046 4 12 4ZM8.53513 4C9.22675 2.8044 10.5194 2 12 2C13.4806 2 14.7733 2.8044 15.4649 4H17C18.6569 4 20 5.34315 20 7V19C20 20.6569 18.6569 22 17 22H7C5.34315 22 4 20.6569 4 19V7C4 5.34315 5.34315 4 7 4H8.53513ZM8 6H7C6.44772 6 6 6.44772 6 7V19C6 19.5523 6.44772 20 7 20H17C17.5523 20 18 19.5523 18 19V7C18 6.44772 17.5523 6 17 6H16C16 7.10457 15.1046 8 14 8H10C8.89543 8 8 7.10457 8 6Z" fill="currentColor"></path></svg>Copy code</button></span></div><div class="p-4 overflow-y-auto"><code class="!whitespace-pre hljs language-plaintext">fake-news-classification/

section headers:

Fake News Classification Project
Overview
This repository contains the code and resources for a Fake News Classification project. The primary goal of this project is to develop and evaluate various machine learning models for distinguishing between real and fake news articles.

Dataset
The dataset used for this project, named WELFake, consists of 72,134 news articles. It includes 35,028 real news articles and 37,106 fake news articles. The dataset is a combination of four popular news datasets (Kaggle, McIntire, Reuters, BuzzFeed Political) to prevent overfitting and enhance the model's training data. Each entry in the dataset has four columns: Serial number, Title, Text, and Label (0 for fake, 1 for real).

The dataset has been published in IEEE Transactions on Computational Social Systems, with the reference: DOI 10.1109/TCSS.2021.3068519.

Steps Performed
Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA): Analyzed the dataset to gain insights into its structure and characteristics.

Data Processing: Preprocessed the data to prepare it for model training, including cleaning and handling missing values.

Modeling: Implemented various machine learning algorithms for classification:

Naive Bayes Classifier
Logistic Regression
Support Vector Machine
Random Forest Classifier
Neural Network using Tokenization and Padding
Long Short Term Memory (LSTM) Neural Network
Results:

Accuracy - Naive Bayes: 0.84
Accuracy - Logistic Regression: 0.94
Accuracy - Support Vector Machine: 0.94
Accuracy - Random Forest Algorithm: 0.95
Accuracy - Neural Network: 0.93
Accuracy - LSTM Neural Network: 0.94
Summary:

This project showcases the application of exploratory data analysis, data preprocessing, and various machine learning algorithms for fake news classification. Multiple models, ranging from traditional machine learning algorithms to complex neural network architectures, were explored. The Random Forest Classifier achieved the highest accuracy at 95%, while both LSTM Neural Network and SVM demonstrated competitive performance with accuracies of 94%.

These results highlight the effectiveness of different modeling techniques in distinguishing between real and fake news articles. The project provides valuable insights into the strengths and performances of various models, offering a comprehensive exploration of approaches for fake news classification.</div></div></div><div class="markdown prose w-full break-words dark:prose-invert dark"><p>Choosing a good repository name is important for clarity, searchability, and professionalism. Here are some common naming standards and best practices for naming your GitHub repository:</p><ol><li><p><strong>Descriptive and Concise:</strong></p><ul><li>Choose a name that clearly describes the purpose or content of the repository.</li><li>Keep it concise to make it easy to remember and type.</li></ul></li><li><p><strong>Avoid Special Characters:</strong></p><ul><li>Stick to alphanumeric characters and hyphens.</li><li>Avoid spaces or special characters that can cause issues in URLs or command-line interactions.</li></ul></li><li><p><strong>Lowercase Letters:</strong></p><ul><li>Use lowercase letters to ensure consistency and avoid confusion.</li></ul></li><li><p><strong>No Underscores:</strong></p><ul><li>While underscores are allowed, using hyphens is more common and aligns with standard naming conventions.</li></ul></li><li><p><strong>Relevance to Project:</strong></p><ul><li>Ensure that the repository name reflects the main functionality or purpose of the project.</li><li>Avoid overly generic names that might be ambiguous.</li></ul></li><li><p><strong>Consistency:</strong></p><ul><li>If you have multiple related repositories, consider using a consistent naming scheme to tie them together.</li></ul></li><li><p><strong>Avoid Abbreviations:</strong></p><ul><li>While abbreviations can be useful, avoid overly cryptic abbreviations that may be unclear to others.</li></ul></li><li><p><strong>Use Keywords:</strong></p><ul><li>Include relevant keywords in the name to enhance searchability.</li></ul></li><li><p><strong>CamelCase or Hyphens:</strong></p><ul><li>Choose a consistent style, either CamelCase (e.g., <code>MyProject</code>) or hyphens (e.g., <code>my-project</code>), and stick with it.</li></ul></li><li><p><strong>No Leading Numbers:</strong></p><ul><li>GitHub repositories cannot start with a number, so avoid leading numeric characters.</li></ul></li><li><p><strong>Unique:</strong></p><ul><li>Ensure that the name is unique and not already in use by another popular project.</li></ul></li><li><p><strong>Consider Length:</strong></p><ul><li>Keep the name reasonably short, but long enough to be descriptive.</li></ul></li></ol><p>Examples based on these standards:</p><ul><li><p><strong>Good Names:</strong></p><ul><li><code>twitter-streaming-analysis</code></li><li><code>realtime-tweet-insights</code></li><li><code>tweet-flow-analyzer</code></li></ul></li><li><p><strong>Avoid:</strong></p><ul><li><code>MyCoolProject</code> (not descriptive)</li><li><code>project_123</code> (includes underscore)</li><li><code>twa8789</code> (not descriptive, includes numbers)</li></ul></li></ul><p>Remember to check for name availability on GitHub to avoid conflicts with existing projects. Following these standards will contribute to a clean and professional appearance for your repository.</p></div></div></div><div class="mt-1 flex justify-start gap-3 empty:hidden"><div <code>requirements.txt</code> file from a Jupyter notebook can be done using the <code>pipreqs</code> tool. This tool automatically scans your code for dependencies and generates a <code>requirements.txt</code> file. Here are the steps to do this:</p><ol><li><p><strong>Install pipreqs:</strong>
Open your terminal or command prompt and run the following command to install <code>pipreqs</code>:</p><pre><div class="dark bg-gray-950 rounded-md"><div class="flex items-center relative text-token-text-secondary bg-token-main-surface-secondary px-4 py-2 text-xs font-sans justify-between rounded-t-md"><span>bash</span><span class="" data-state="closed"><button class="flex gap-1 items-center"><svg width="24" height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="icon-sm"><path fill-rule="evenodd" clip-rule="evenodd" d="M12 4C10.8954 4 10 4.89543 10 6H14C14 4.89543 13.1046 4 12 4ZM8.53513 4C9.22675 2.8044 10.5194 2 12 2C13.4806 2 14.7733 2.8044 15.4649 4H17C18.6569 4 20 5.34315 20 7V19C20 20.6569 18.6569 22 17 22H7C5.34315 22 4 20.6569 4 19V7C4 5.34315 5.34315 4 7 4H8.53513ZM8 6H7C6.44772 6 6 6.44772 6 7V19C6 19.5523 6.44772 20 7 20H17C17.5523 20 18 19.5523 18 19V7C18 6.44772 17.5523 6 17 6H16C16 7.10457 15.1046 8 14 8H10C8.89543 8 8 7.10457 8 6Z" fill="currentColor"></path></svg>Copy code</button></span></div><div class="p-4 overflow-y-auto"><code class="!whitespace-pre hljs language-bash">pip install pipreqs
</code></div></div></pre></li><li><p><strong>Navigate to your project directory:</strong>
Open a terminal or command prompt, and navigate to the directory where your Jupyter notebook is located.</p></li><li><p><strong>Generate <code>requirements.txt</code>:</strong>
Run the following command to generate the <code>requirements.txt</code> file:</p><pre><div class="dark bg-gray-950 rounded-md"><div class="flex items-center relative text-token-text-secondary bg-token-main-surface-secondary px-4 py-2 text-xs font-sans justify-between rounded-t-md"><span>bash</span><span class="" data-state="closed"><button class="flex gap-1 items-center"><svg width="24" height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="icon-sm"><path fill-rule="evenodd" clip-rule="evenodd" d="M12 4C10.8954 4 10 4.89543 10 6H14C14 4.89543 13.1046 4 12 4ZM8.53513 4C9.22675 2.8044 10.5194 2 12 2C13.4806 2 14.7733 2.8044 15.4649 4H17C18.6569 4 20 5.34315 20 7V19C20 20.6569 18.6569 22 17 22H7C5.34315 22 4 20.6569 4 19V7C4 5.34315 5.34315 4 7 4H8.53513ZM8 6H7C6.44772 6 6 6.44772 6 7V19C6 19.5523 6.44772 20 7 20H17C17.5523 20 18 19.5523 18 19V7C18 6.44772 17.5523 6 17 6H16C16 7.10457 15.1046 8 14 8H10C8.89543 8 8 7.10457 8 6Z" fill="currentColor"></path></svg>Copy code</button></span></div><div class="p-4 overflow-y-auto"><code class="!whitespace-pre hljs language-bash">pipreqs .
</code></div></div></pre><p>This command will scan the current directory (recursively) for Python files and create a <code>requirements.txt</code> file with the detected dependencies.</p></li><li><p><strong>Review and Edit:</strong>
